<major-heading id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2008-12-22.0.mh" nospeaker="True" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-08/wa1222.htm">Written Answers Monday 22 December 2008</major-heading>

<major-heading id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2008-12-22.1.mh" nospeaker="True" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-08/wa1222.htm">Scottish Executive</major-heading>

<minor-heading id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2008-12-22.S3W-18671.h" nospeaker="True" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-08/wa1222.htm#1">British Sign Language</minor-heading>

<ques id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2008-12-22.S3W-18671.q0" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/80283" speakername="Jackie Baillie (Dumbarton) (Lab)" spid="S3W-18671" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-08/wa1222.htm#1">

  <p>To ask the Scottish Executive whether it routinely translates Scottish Government information into British Sign Language.</p>

</ques>


<reply id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2008-12-22.S3W-18671.r0" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/80349" speakername="Stewart Maxwell" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-08/wa1222.htm#1">

  <p>The Scottish Government recognises the importance of making information accessible to British Sign Language (BSL) users. We routinely provide BSL interpreters for meetings if BSL users will be present, and we consider providing BSL DVD translations of publications where appropriate, or if it is not appropriate, ensure that the relevant information is communicated to BSL users in a suitable way.</p>

</reply>


<minor-heading id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2008-12-22.S3W-18578.h" nospeaker="True" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-08/wa1222.htm#2">Lone Parents</minor-heading>

<ques id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2008-12-22.S3W-18578.q0" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/80285" speakername="Claire Baker (Mid Scotland and Fife) (Lab)" spid="S3W-18578" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-08/wa1222.htm#2" holdingdate="2008-12-19">

  <p>To ask the Scottish Executive how many people (a) applied for and (b) received a Lone Parent&rsquo;s Grant in each of the last three years.</p>

</ques>


<reply id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2008-12-22.S3W-18578.r0" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/80330" speakername="Fiona Hyslop" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-08/wa1222.htm#2">

  <p>Information on the number of students who applied for Lone Parent&rsquo;s Grant and Lone Parent&rsquo;s Childcare Grant is not held centrally.</p>

  <p>The following table shows the number of higher education students who received Lone Parent&rsquo;s Grant and the number receiving Lone Parent&rsquo;s Childcare Grant from the Student Awards Agency for Scotland (SAAS) in academic years 2005-06 to 2007-08. These figures are published, for academic years 2002-03 to 2007-08, in <em>Higher Education Student Support in Scotland 2007-08</em>:</p>

  <p><a href="http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Publications/2008/11/21111027/0" target="_blank">http://www.scotland.gov.uk/Publications/2008/11/21111027/0</a>.</p>

  <p><table width="50%" border="BORDER" cellpadding="2" cellspacing="0" bordercolor="#CCCCCC">
<tr>
<td width="17%" align="center" valign="top"> Academic Year</td>
<td width="41%" align="center" valign="top"> Number of Students Receiving Lone Parent&rsquo;s Grant</td>
<td width="41%" align="center" valign="top"> Number of Students Receiving Lone Parent&rsquo;s Childcare Grant</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td width="17%" align="left" valign="top"> 2005-06</td>
<td width="41%" align="right" valign="top"> 3,230</td>
<td width="41%" align="right" valign="top"> 1,450</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td width="17%" align="left" valign="top"> 2006-07</td>
<td width="41%" align="right" valign="top"> 3,025</td>
<td width="41%" align="right" valign="top"> 1,415</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td width="17%" align="left" valign="top"> 2007-08</td>
<td width="41%" align="right" valign="top"> 2,920</td>
<td width="41%" align="right" valign="top"> 1,375</td>
</tr>
</table></p>

  <p>Notes:</p>

  <p>Student Awards Agency for Scotland (SAAS).</p>

  <p>Student numbers have been rounded up or down to the nearest five (e.g. one, two round down to zero, three, four round up to five).</p>

  <p>Lone Parent&rsquo;s Grant is available on an income assessed basis to students who are single, widowed, divorced or no longer living with a partner and are bringing up children. An additional grant, Lone Parent&rsquo;s Childcare Grant, is available to recipients of Lone Parent&rsquo;s Grant who have to pay for registered or formal child care.</p>

</reply>


<minor-heading id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2008-12-22.S3W-19062.h" nospeaker="True" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-08/wa1222.htm#3">Non-Domestic Rates</minor-heading>

<ques id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2008-12-22.S3W-19062.q0" speakerid="uk.org.publicwhip/member/80378" speakername="Jeremy Purvis (Tweeddale, Ettrick and Lauderdale) (LD)" spid="S3W-19062" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-08/wa1222.htm#3">

  <p>To ask the Scottish Executive how many people have been successfully prosecuted for non-payment of business rates in each of the last 24 months.</p>

</ques>


<reply id="uk.org.publicwhip/spwa/2008-12-22.S3W-19062.r0" speakerid="unknown" speakername="Frank Mulholland QC" url="http://www.scottish.parliament.uk/business/pqa/wa-08/wa1222.htm#3">

  <p>There can be no prosecutions for simple non-payment of non-domestic rates, since it is a civil matter.</p>

</reply>
